00:20:11,700 --> 00:20:16,640
blotter. It wouldn't burn alone. It would burn in front of the person who needed to see it.

231
00:20:16,640 --> 00:20:22,120
I went up again. I leaned my forehead against the door one last time that night. Good night,

232
00:20:22,260 --> 00:20:29,220
I'll under. On the other side, a second. Two. And a whisper so low I could have invented it. Good

233
00:20:29,220 --> 00:20:35,800
night. I didn't invent it. She said it. Saturday was born gray with a pale light striking sideways

234
00:20:35,800 --> 00:20:41,540
at the shutters and streaking the floor with opaque bands. I got up before the heat pressed in.

235
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:47,020
Took a long bath, chose a light dress, pinned my hair up with the two hands that no longer

236
00:20:47,020 --> 00:20:51,880
trembled so much. I opened the door of the old contract room and stepped out for the first time in

237
00:20:51,880 --> 00:20:57,560
almost 40 hours. I didn't go looking for him. I knew that at nine he'd be with Fausto in the downstairs

238
00:20:57,560 --> 00:21:02,800
office. I went down the opposite side of the staircase and headed to the winter garden where Dona

239
00:21:02,800 --> 00:21:07,260
Kiarra's brameleads caught the light through the glass and everything seemed quieter than the rest

240
00:21:07,260 --> 00:21:13,260
of the house. Dona Kiarra appeared with a tray before I asked. Camo-Mail-T, a small piece of bread

