I no longer found cold. I found it deliberate. There was a difference. I picked up my cup with both hands.

739
01:08:40,630 --> 01:08:47,370
felt the warmth enter my fingers and asked nothing more. Someone in Providence would no longer

740
01:08:47,370 --> 01:08:53,950
send word with dead flowers. That was all I needed to know. The rest I left with him.

741
01:08:54,810 --> 01:08:58,270
Nareena appeared in the doorway carrying a white box wrapped in green ribbon.

742
01:08:59,430 --> 01:09:04,550
Cake. She announced. In that way she had of turning every entrance into an act.

743
01:09:05,610 --> 01:09:11,090
Before anyone asks why. Bastion got up and pulled a chair for her. Without a word.

744
01:09:11,570 --> 01:09:14,730
Without taking his eyes off the window. Nareena looked at the chair.

745
01:09:15,270 --> 01:09:20,050
Looked at him. Sat. Arranging the boxes ribbon on the table as if she'd seen nothing.

746
01:09:20,570 --> 01:09:24,950
You know that stone face turned out kind of handsome after the coffee. She said,

747
01:09:25,310 --> 01:09:29,710
loud enough for Donna Kiarra to hear from the kitchen. Bastion coughed into a hand.

748
01:09:29,710 --> 01:09:35,350
Change the subject by asking Donna Kiarra for another plate. I filed it away somewhere inside me.

749
01:09:35,670 --> 01:09:40,550
The chair pulled out and the evirted look and the cough that wasn't a cough. And I didn't comment.

750
01:09:41,150 --> 01:09:45,810
There were stories that weren't mine yet. Seven weeks later, the garden was covered in flowers.

751
01:09:46,410 --> 01:09:52,790
I didn't wear a veil. I chose a simple dress, cut at the waist, no train and no adornment I'd need to carry.

752
01:09:53,190 --> 01:09:57,530
The bouquet was of chameleas. The same ones I'd been watering since the start of that spring

753
01:09:57,530 --> 01:10:02,250
and pot scattered along the corridor window. A small routine that had become mine without my

754
01:10:02,250 --> 01:10:07,930
noticing the exact moment. Nareena had helped me tie the white ribbon around the stems the night before.

755
01:10:08,270 --> 01:10:12,550
Crying while she laughed at herself, which was exactly her way of being happy for someone.

756
01:10:13,010 --> 01:10:18,050
I walked to the altar alone. There was no one to give me away. And even if there had been,

757
01:10:18,390 --> 01:10:22,690
I wouldn't have accepted. No one gives away a woman who has already given herself.

758
01:10:22,690 --> 01:10:27,930
The morning sun came in slanted between the rows of chairs. And the shadows of the rose stems

759
01:10:27,930 --> 01:10:33,890
on the arch fell in long streaks over the stone path. I heard my own footsteps. They were the only ones.

760
01:10:34,270 --> 01:10:38,850
Ludovico waited beneath the arch with his father's old watch on his wrist and his arms at his sides.

761
01:10:39,270 --> 01:10:46,830
Not crossed, hiding nothing behind them. He was in a dark suit. No tie. When he saw me arrive, he swallowed.

762
01:10:47,410 --> 01:10:52,350
I saw the movement in his throat. I also saw the effort he made not to let more than that show.

763
01:10:52,690 --> 01:10:55,890
And I saw that the effort wasn't enough. Nareena cried,

764
01:10:56,170 --> 01:11:02,430
prettyly, seated in the front row, with Donna Kiarra's hand over hers. Donna Kiarra cried in an ugly

765
01:11:02,430 --> 01:11:08,110
way, an embroidered handkerchief pressed to her nose. Her shoulders shaking in generous silence.

766
01:11:08,810 --> 01:11:14,690
Bastion was in a tie as few times as I'd ever seen him. A dark gray tie, meticulously nodded.

767
01:11:15,190 --> 01:11:19,430
The only sign that that morning was different from all the others. Nareena turned to the nearest

768
01:11:19,430 --> 01:11:24,590
person and said it loud enough to reach the altar. If he blinked twice in a row, she said,

769
01:11:25,030 --> 01:11:30,430
it's a smile. Bastion blinked twice in a row, without turning his face. I saw it.

770
01:11:30,750 --> 01:11:35,910
Atavia was in the front row on the right side, in a dark blue wool dress, and the bearing of

771
01:11:35,910 --> 01:11:41,410
someone who came because she needed to be seen. She was invited. She accepted out of politics.

772
01:11:42,130 --> 01:11:47,310
I didn't look at her once, and when the priest began to speak, I realized I also wouldn't need

773
01:11:47,310 --> 01:11:54,150
to. The priest said short things. Ludovico said his vow so low that the chameleas barely heard it,

774
01:11:54,310 --> 01:11:59,530
but I heard it. He said he'd learned, too late, that love isn't guaranteed with a clause,

775
01:11:59,910 --> 01:12:04,290
that he'd spend the rest of his life without writing any exit door for me. That if one day I

776
01:12:04,290 --> 01:12:09,370
wanted to leave, it would have to be me walking, because he'd no longer build the exit with his own hands.

777
01:12:09,770 --> 01:12:15,650
I said my vow looking at him. I chose to stay. I'll keep choosing every day. He kissed me with

778
01:12:15,650 --> 01:12:21,430
no contract between us. No door. With the morning sun on my back in the smell of Camilla in the air,

779
01:12:21,830 --> 01:12:26,470
and his hands on both sides of my face, as if I were the only stable thing in a world he'd

780
01:12:26,470 --> 01:12:32,270
spent his whole life trying to control. Winter came heavy in Providence. Enrico was born on a

781
01:12:32,270 --> 01:12:38,890
late January dawn, with snow falling outside the window and thick quiet pieces. No wind, as if time

782
01:12:38,890 --> 01:12:45,150
had decided to be gentle at that hour. Labor was long. Ludovico didn't leave the room once. He

783
01:12:45,150 --> 01:12:50,290
held my hand through every contraction. His forehead pressed to mine. murmuring things in

784
01:12:50,290 --> 01:12:54,750
Italian that I'd begun to understand because of how much he murmured near me in hours without witnesses.

785
01:12:55,270 --> 01:13:00,730
Outside, Narina waited with Donna Kiarra, and an absurd basket with enough sandwiches to

786
01:13:00,730 --> 01:13:06,570
feed a whole battalion, because that was her way of enduring the weight. Bastion stood in the corridor

787
01:13:06,570 --> 01:13:13,270
with the gun hidden under his jacket, protecting something that had no enemy that dawn. Enrico came

788
01:13:13,270 --> 01:13:18,290
into the world with a strong cry. The size the family had waited for over three generations.

789
01:13:19,490 --> 01:13:24,830
The obstetrician placed him on my chest first. He stopped crying almost at once,

790
01:13:25,150 --> 01:13:30,910
as if he recognized the place. I stayed looking at him. That tiny piece of a person with wet

791
01:13:30,910 --> 01:13:36,450
black lashes and hands closed into small fists, and I found no word sufficient for what I felt.

792
01:13:36,890 --> 01:13:42,470
I didn't try. Ludovico took him afterward. He held his son in his arms with both hands open.

793
01:13:42,470 --> 01:13:48,210
The small body lost in his large arms, and stayed motionless for a few seconds just looking.

794
01:13:48,690 --> 01:13:54,670
And that was when he wept. He didn't hide it. He didn't turn his face. He didn't run his hand

795
01:13:54,670 --> 01:14:00,170
over his eyes as if wiping away something else. He wept looking at his son. His chin trembling

796
01:14:00,170 --> 01:14:04,970
and the tears running down the line of his jaw without him making any gesture to stop them.

797
01:14:05,170 --> 01:14:11,270
With a stillness that was only his, and that I'd never seen in any of the faces he used in the

798
01:14:11,270 --> 01:14:18,550
nose. He said low to me when he found his voice. Poor thing. I answered. He laughed in the middle

799
01:14:18,550 --> 01:14:23,930
of the weeping. He leaned his forehead against mine. That gesture that had become our private language.

800
01:14:24,470 --> 01:14:29,210
Then he leaned his forehead against in Riko's too, closing the triangle among the three of us.

801
01:14:29,490 --> 01:14:34,670
And we stayed like that for a time I couldn't measure. In Riko, he said, you were right.

802
01:14:35,130 --> 01:14:40,210
I'd suggested the name weeks before. On an ordinary night while we waited for the snow to stop outside.

803
01:14:40,210 --> 01:14:46,370
And Riko, in honor of his brother, the one who died at 19 in a story he told me only once.

804
01:14:46,770 --> 01:14:51,710
Slowly, without a dormant. Lutaviko had looked at me for a long time when I said it.

805
01:14:51,970 --> 01:14:56,510
Without saying yes or no, as if he needed to carry the name a little before giving his answer.

806
01:14:57,050 --> 01:15:02,410
Only now, with his son and his arms and the weeping he didn't hide, was he saying yes.

807
01:15:02,930 --> 01:15:08,170
Six months after the birth, the morning in the suite was one of the calmest the mansion had ever seen.

808
01:15:08,170 --> 01:15:13,390
And Riko slept in the crib in the room next door. And the monitor beside my side of the bed,

809
01:15:13,910 --> 01:15:18,230
purred with his breathing. That sound that had become the soundtrack of my small hours.

810
01:15:18,730 --> 01:15:22,630
The June light came through the cracks and the shutters and wide warm bands.

811
01:15:23,050 --> 01:15:29,450
Lutaviko came in carrying a tray with two cups, bear foot, no jacket, in the previous day's shirt.

812
01:15:29,870 --> 01:15:34,750
He sat on the edge of the bed and handed me mine. Two sugar cubes, a drop of milk.

813
01:15:34,750 --> 01:15:40,350
I laughed softly. The way one laughs at an old joke that keeps working out of love for what it means.

814
01:15:40,770 --> 01:15:46,910
Do you remember? I asked. That I told you once months ago, my mother's dream. He already knew

815
01:15:46,910 --> 01:15:53,270
which question it was. I saw it in the way he held his own cup. Unhurried. He let me finish anyway.

816
01:15:53,850 --> 01:15:58,670
A library I continued. In federal hill, free books for the neighborhood children.

817
01:15:59,210 --> 01:16:03,230
She never had money to put a book in my hand that wasn't borrowed from the school or from someone

818
01:16:03,230 --> 01:16:08,290
who owed a favor. I bought the building three months ago. He answered, looking at his cup.

819
01:16:08,810 --> 01:16:13,070
The work began last Monday. I didn't tell you because I wanted it to be a surprise when the

820
01:16:13,070 --> 01:16:18,870
sign went up. It was going up next week. I stayed quiet. The band of sun crossed the sheet slowly.

821
01:16:19,430 --> 01:16:26,930
The sign. I asked softly. What's it going to say? Marcecano Community Library. Your mother's maiden name.

822
01:16:27,270 --> 01:16:32,850
You told me one dinner night and passing. The way one tells something without expecting anyone to keep it.

823
01:16:32,850 --> 01:16:37,390
I kept it. I set the cup on the nightstand before I could spill the coffee over the sheet.

824
01:16:37,850 --> 01:16:41,190
I leaned my forehead against his. We stayed like that a good while,

825
01:16:41,710 --> 01:16:46,650
without either of us finding a word worth more than the silence. In Rico woke shortly after.

826
01:16:47,190 --> 01:16:52,530
I nursed him. Changed him. Handed him to Ludovico so he could make the baby laugh with that stone

827
01:16:52,530 --> 01:16:57,090
face that no longer fooled anyone. At the end of the morning we went down to the winter garden.

828
01:16:57,430 --> 01:17:02,550
I took in Rico in my arm so he could see the chameleas. The same ones that had become my bouquet.

829
01:17:02,850 --> 01:17:08,350
And that I still watered now with him on my hip, showing him the flowers as if he knew what they were.

830
01:17:09,410 --> 01:17:15,350
Maybe he did. Ludovico sat beside me on the stone bench with the coffee he'd brought down from upstairs.

831
01:17:16,110 --> 01:17:22,250
Still warm. The June sun came through the glass panes at a low angle, warming the stone without burning.

832
01:17:22,810 --> 01:17:28,270
Do you remember the morning? He said in a low tone. When I received an envelope and put it in the drawer,

833
01:17:28,270 --> 01:17:33,830
I remembered at once. The morning after the night everything had shifted sides. On the other side

834
01:17:33,830 --> 01:17:39,830
of months, and of all that came after. The old envelope sealed with the crest of the lion with the broken

835
01:17:39,830 --> 01:17:46,250
crown. He'd put it away unopened in front of me and hugged me too tight for an ordinary Saturday morning.

836
01:17:46,770 --> 01:17:52,830
I remember. I answered. You hugged me too tight for it to be nothing. He ran his hand slowly over

837
01:17:52,830 --> 01:17:58,270
Rico's hair, who slept against my shoulder with his mouth slightly open. It really was nothing.

838
01:17:58,930 --> 01:18:04,430
Just the beginning. I stayed looking at him. The winter garden was in a good silence. The kind

839
01:18:04,430 --> 01:18:10,590
that asks for no filling. In Rico breathe deep against my neck. Ludovico's hand was open over mine

840
01:18:10,590 --> 01:18:17,130
between the two bodies in the middle of the stone bench, without grip, without weight. Just there.

841
01:18:17,570 --> 01:18:21,930
I thought of the islanda who'd waited at the altar of the church and providence in a white dress

842
01:18:21,930 --> 01:18:27,650
with a bell-tolling 12 times to say what the whole city already knew. She was another person.

843
01:18:28,310 --> 01:18:34,490
She was me, but she was another person. The one who didn't yet know that humiliation can be the first

844
01:18:34,490 --> 01:18:40,670
step of a path worth walking. Ludovico raised my hand and kissed my wrist. Slowly, without announcement.

845
01:18:41,410 --> 01:18:47,450
In Rico let out a small sigh on my shoulder. Outside, the white chameleas swayed lightly with the wind

846
01:18:47,450 --> 01:18:53,050
coming through the gap in the garden door. The butt wife of Providence had a price. No one,

847
01:18:53,130 --> 01:18:55,370
not even he knew it was this, to stay.
